## OBS Lecture Slide Workflow

### Creating slides at 608×738px for OBS

1. **Create a new design:** canva.com → **Custom size** → 608 × 738px → **Create new design**
2. **Design all slides as pages within one Canva project.** Each page = one lecture slide. Use the page panel on the left to add, reorder, and duplicate pages.
3. **Build a master template page first:** one slide with your standard layout (myth title zone, content zone, image zone, branding). Lock the background (Ctrl+Shift+K) before editing slide-specific content.
4. **Duplicate the template** for each new slide: right-click the page thumbnail → Duplicate page. Or use the duplicate page button.
5. **Batch export:** Share → Download → PNG → check "All pages" → Download. Each page exports as a separately numbered PNG file (e.g. design-page-1.png, design-page-2.png).
6. **In OBS:** Add each PNG as an Image source in your Lecture Scene, positioned at x=656, y=342, sized at 608×738px to fit the center column below your facecam.

### Key design principles for lecture slides at 608px wide

- Minimum font size: 24–28pt for any text you want readable after OBS stream compression
- Keep each slide to one core idea — myth name, one supporting image, one line of context
- Export as PNG (not JPG) for crisp text
- Use Cinzel or Cinzel Decorative for myth titles — appropriate for mythology aesthetic, available free
- Use Cormorant Garamond for secondary/descriptive text — elegant and readable at small sizes
- The Glow effect (free) on myth art images gives an otherworldly quality — worth experimenting with

### Transparent overlay workaround for OBS (if needed)

Since transparent PNG export is Pro-only, if you ever need a Canva element as an OBS overlay without a background:
1. Set the background to **bright green (#00FF00)** in Canva
2. Export as standard PNG
3. In OBS, add as an Image source → right-click → Filters → add **Chroma Key** filter → set key color to green
4. This removes the green background and leaves only your overlay elements visible

For E.I. Werner's standard lecture slides (solid background panels), this workaround is not needed.

